00:04:57.710 --> 00:05:01.790
So let me tell you a little
bit about a story that I had.

00:05:01.790 --> 00:05:05.770
So when I first went
out and hired folks,

00:05:05.770 --> 00:05:10.440
I think it was the seventh
hire I made in 2008.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:13.430
And I was able to
nab the number one

00:05:13.430 --> 00:05:17.400
salesperson from an 800 person
sales team here in Boston.

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:18.790
It wasn't Google.

00:05:18.790 --> 00:05:20.270
It was a public company.

00:05:20.270 --> 00:05:21.971
And I was psyched.

00:05:21.971 --> 00:05:23.470
I had somehow
convinced them that we

00:05:23.470 --> 00:05:25.700
were going to be the
next big deal in town,

00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:27.330
and they decided to come over.

00:05:27.330 --> 00:05:29.220
And I was surprised
that that person did not

00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:30.585
crush it at our company.

00:05:30.585 --> 00:05:31.460
I thought they would.

00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:33.626
I thought they would come
in and completely teach us

00:05:33.626 --> 00:05:34.800
how to sell.

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:36.950
And as I stood back
and thought about it,

00:05:36.950 --> 00:05:39.270
and reflected on
that situation, I

00:05:39.270 --> 00:05:42.050
realized that they came from
such a different context

00:05:42.050 --> 00:05:43.480
than where we were selling.

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:45.649
They came from this
enormous brand.

00:05:45.649 --> 00:05:46.690
They picked up the phone.

00:05:46.690 --> 00:05:49.870
People knew exactly what was
coming in terms of the pitch.

00:05:49.870 --> 00:05:51.830
It was a very
transactional sale.

00:05:51.830 --> 00:05:55.172
It was usually a
same-call decision.

00:05:55.172 --> 00:05:57.380
And they would do as much
activity as [? probable. ?]

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:58.580
That led to success.

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:01.170
That couldn't have been more
different than the context

00:06:01.170 --> 00:06:03.360
that we were selling at
HubSpot in the early days.

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:05.119
No one had a clue who we were.

00:06:05.119 --> 00:06:07.410
We told them we are selling
inbound marketing software.

00:06:07.410 --> 00:06:09.560
They had no idea what
inbound marketing was.

00:06:09.560 --> 00:06:12.960
It was a very evangelistic
consultative sell.

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:16.630
And it made be understand
that when hiring managers

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:18.500
and when entrepreneurs
ask me, well,

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:20.480
what do you look for
in a salesperson?

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:23.560
It's almost like an
irrelevant question.

00:06:23.560 --> 00:06:26.030
Because it so depends
on their unique context,

00:06:26.030 --> 00:06:29.180
and how complex their sale
is, who they're selling to,

00:06:29.180 --> 00:06:30.310
et cetera.

00:06:30.310 --> 00:06:33.590
So that was my first takeaway is
the ideal sales hiring formula

00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:35.320
is different for every company.

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:37.470
However, I do
think that there is

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:40.080
a consistent process on how
that formula can actually

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:41.261
be engineered.

00:06:41.261 --> 00:06:43.760
And I think this is something
that you guys do exceptionally

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:44.620
well.

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:48.700
And it's something that I
just, using my engineering

00:06:48.700 --> 00:06:50.550
background, kind
of instinctively

00:06:50.550 --> 00:06:52.750
try to go at this in terms
of predicting success.

00:06:52.750 --> 00:06:56.840
So the first year, I
wrote down the 10 criteria

00:06:56.840 --> 00:06:58.890
that I thought would
correlate with success

00:06:58.890 --> 00:07:00.020
in our environment.

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:02.630
I clearly defined what
each criteria was.

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:05.960
I clearly defined what a score
of a 1 to 3, or a 5 to 7,

00:07:05.960 --> 00:07:08.630
or an 8 to 10 would look like.

00:07:08.630 --> 00:07:10.990
And I was disciplined about
scoring every single hire

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:12.730
against that criteria.

00:07:12.730 --> 00:07:15.610
And the nice thing about
sales, unlike engineering

00:07:15.610 --> 00:07:18.460
and marketing and
other disciplines,

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:22.530
is it's probably the most
quantitative function where

00:07:22.530 --> 00:07:24.950
you can quantify success.

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:27.220
And by following
this process, it

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:30.270
allowed me to reflect
on the first six hires,

00:07:30.270 --> 00:07:32.190
the first twelve
hires that I made,

00:07:32.190 --> 00:07:35.180
and start to pick up patterns
as to what's predicting success

00:07:35.180 --> 00:07:38.490
and what's not, and
iterate on that approach.

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:40.660
And it wasn't, long
probably about 18 months in,

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:43.640
where, as a young startup, I
was able to do a regression

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:47.320
analysis against
predicting success,

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:49.860
and attainment rate,
and revenue success,

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:51.650
and that kind of stuff,
with the criteria

00:07:51.650 --> 00:07:54.420
that I was actually observing
during the interview process.

00:07:54.420 --> 00:07:56.790
So this is the results of
the first regression analysis

00:07:56.790 --> 00:07:57.800
that I did.

00:07:57.800 --> 00:08:01.550
And this evolved a little
bit from where we ended up.

00:08:01.550 --> 00:08:03.220
What was really
interesting about this

00:08:03.220 --> 00:08:08.060
was some of the criteria
that you typically associate

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:11.500
with a good salesperson,
maybe in like a car sales

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:14.400
environment, something we
think is a traditional sales

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:18.730
environment, like closing
ability, convincing, objection

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:22.420
handling, those are actually
negatively correlated

00:08:22.420 --> 00:08:24.320
with success in our model.

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:26.120
And things that
you would associate

00:08:26.120 --> 00:08:28.880
with a great
consultant or a coach,

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:31.190
like preparation, and
domain experience,

00:08:31.190 --> 00:08:34.830
and intelligence, those
were most highly correlated.

00:08:34.830 --> 00:08:38.610
So I thought this was a really
cool outcome that there's

00:08:38.610 --> 00:08:42.610
been a lot of chat about how
the buyer behaviors change,

00:08:42.610 --> 00:08:44.890
and sales needs to change,
and all that kind of stuff.

00:08:44.890 --> 00:08:49.570
And this was some form
of statistical proof

00:08:49.570 --> 00:08:52.730
that the buyers wanted a
different type of salesperson

00:08:52.730 --> 00:08:55.330
that was less the person that
was jamming concepts down

00:08:55.330 --> 00:08:58.310
your throat, and more someone
that they could trust, respect,

00:08:58.310 --> 00:09:00.580
get advisement from, and
appreciate through the sales

00:09:00.580 --> 00:09:01.700
process.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:06.150
So there were five criteria
over time in our context

00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:08.010
that correlated with success.

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:14.070
And I do believe that in a
lot of tech entrepreneurship

00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:18.680
situations, these five criteria
actually correlate pretty well.

00:09:18.680 --> 00:09:20.920
I'll poll you guys to
see how you do here.

00:09:20.920 --> 00:09:23.552
So these three are
all in the top five.

00:09:23.552 --> 00:09:25.600
One of them is number
one, obviously.

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:30.290
So how many think intelligence
is the number one correlating

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:33.400
criteria in our environment?

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:36.220
How about coach-ability?

00:09:36.220 --> 00:09:37.720
How about curiosity?

00:09:37.720 --> 00:09:38.220
OK.

00:09:38.220 --> 00:09:38.801
Cool.

00:09:38.801 --> 00:09:39.300
I got you.

00:09:39.300 --> 00:09:41.030
Curiosity was number two.

00:09:41.030 --> 00:09:43.240
Coach-ability was
actually number one.

00:09:43.240 --> 00:09:46.290
And what was really interesting
about that was coach-ability

00:09:46.290 --> 00:09:51.010
wasn't even in my first
set of the 10 criteria

00:09:51.010 --> 00:09:51.750
that I laid out.

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:54.130
It didn't come
until a year later

00:09:54.130 --> 00:09:58.580
when I looked and saw some
people who were absolutely

00:09:58.580 --> 00:10:00.490
crushing it at their
last job, but they

00:10:00.490 --> 00:10:01.640
weren't doing well here.

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:04.670
And they were the types of folks
that just locked themselves

00:10:04.670 --> 00:10:07.460
in the room and weren't open to
the training and the coaching.

00:10:07.460 --> 00:10:08.160
They were like, you know what?

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:08.730
I know how to sell.

00:10:08.730 --> 00:10:10.170
I've been selling for 10 years.

00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:11.230
Let me just go figure it out.

00:10:11.230 --> 00:10:13.550
And they were the folks that
actually ended up failing.

00:10:13.550 --> 00:10:16.390
So it's something that
we had to really get out

00:10:16.390 --> 00:10:17.457
in the interview process.

00:10:17.457 --> 00:10:19.540
So there's coach-ability,
curiosity, intelligence,

00:10:19.540 --> 00:10:21.450
work ethic, and prior success.

00:10:21.450 --> 00:10:24.470
And if there's curiosity
on how I interview on that,

00:10:24.470 --> 00:10:26.730
we can talk about
that during the Q&amp;A.

00:10:26.730 --> 00:10:29.920
So moving onto training.

00:10:29.920 --> 00:10:33.300
What I found with
training was, I first

00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:36.790
interviewed 30 VPs of
sales when I took this job

00:10:36.790 --> 00:10:37.911
in the first year.

00:10:37.911 --> 00:10:39.910
Because I didn't know
what the heck I was doing,

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:41.600
and I'd never done this before.

00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:44.620
And I learned some
stuff from that process.

00:10:44.620 --> 00:10:46.460
But I also found
some things that I

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:47.710
didn't like about the process.

00:10:47.710 --> 00:10:50.234
And training was
certainly one of them.

00:10:50.234 --> 00:10:51.650
It seemed like
when I asked folks,

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:53.840
how do you train
your salespeople?

00:10:53.840 --> 00:10:55.700
They said, hey, Bob,
welcome to the company.

00:10:55.700 --> 00:10:57.770
You remember, Sue, our
number one salesperson

00:10:57.770 --> 00:10:59.022
from the interview process?

00:10:59.022 --> 00:11:01.230
Well, you're going to sit
next to her for two months,

00:11:01.230 --> 00:11:03.360
or you're going to ride
with her for two months.

00:11:03.360 --> 00:11:07.760
And that didn't feel scalable
nor predictable for me.

00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:11.160
So I wanted to challenge
that and create

00:11:11.160 --> 00:11:14.690
a much more predictable
exam-oriented,

00:11:14.690 --> 00:11:17.180
certification-oriented
approach, which we did.

00:11:17.180 --> 00:11:18.880
We introduced a
sales methodology,

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:21.200
and that was very important.

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:24.130
What I found was,
over the years,

00:11:24.130 --> 00:11:26.930
as I looked at our top
performing salespeople,

00:11:26.930 --> 00:11:30.710
each salesperson that
was a top performer

00:11:30.710 --> 00:11:34.330
was a top performer
for a different reason.

00:11:34.330 --> 00:11:39.100
Like I had this guy, Adam, who
was an absolute activity hound.

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:41.850
Every time we generate
our monthly reports,

00:11:41.850 --> 00:11:44.349
he had 40% more activity
than everybody else.

00:11:44.349 --> 00:11:45.640
He would just crush the phones.

00:11:45.640 --> 00:11:47.640
If you went and sat
behind him at his desk,

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:50.647
he had like five
tabs of his CRM open.

00:11:50.647 --> 00:11:51.480
He was on the phone.

00:11:51.480 --> 00:11:52.150
He was writing emails.

00:11:52.150 --> 00:11:52.983
He was taking notes.

00:11:52.983 --> 00:11:53.950
He was a multi-tasker.

00:11:53.950 --> 00:11:55.260
He was insane.

00:11:55.260 --> 00:11:57.680
And he was mediocre
at everything else.

00:11:57.680 --> 00:11:59.427
He wasn't the best
consultative seller.

00:11:59.427 --> 00:12:01.510
He didn't build the best
trust with his prospects.

00:12:01.510 --> 00:12:03.370
He didn't do the
best discovery calls.

00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:06.460
But because he had 40% more
activity than everybody else,

00:12:06.460 --> 00:12:08.520
huge numbers came
out the bottom.

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:10.500
And then I had Jen.

00:12:10.500 --> 00:12:13.160
And Jen was an amazing
rapport builder.

00:12:13.160 --> 00:12:15.960
Like you listened to her
demos, the first half hour

00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:19.750
was about sports, and kids,
and church, and the weather.

00:12:19.750 --> 00:12:22.050
And she was best friends
with every prospect

00:12:22.050 --> 00:12:23.730
that she spoke to.

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:26.000
Now again, didn't give
the best product demo.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.540
Didn't give the best
discovery calls.

00:12:28.540 --> 00:12:32.110
But because her prospect loved
her so much, many, many of them

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:33.300
bought.

00:12:33.300 --> 00:12:35.100
Now they were both
top performing reps.

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:38.860
Imagine if Jen trained
by watching Adam or Adam

00:12:38.860 --> 00:12:41.280
trained by watching Jen.

00:12:41.280 --> 00:12:42.950
They would have
picked up bad habits.

00:12:42.950 --> 00:12:44.320
They would have had
different perception

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:46.153
of their unique superpowers
and whether they

00:12:46.153 --> 00:12:48.210
could use their superpowers
in our environment.

00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:50.419
And I see that happen
time and time again.

00:12:50.419 --> 00:12:51.960
So that's another
reason why I really

00:12:51.960 --> 00:12:55.000
wanted to strive toward
this standard process.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.930
Now beyond that
in training, there

00:12:57.930 --> 00:13:01.140
are two opportunities
that we took advantage of.

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:08.670
One was because the buyers have
a higher expectation from sales

00:13:08.670 --> 00:13:10.860
and want to learn
from them, we thought

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:12.750
it was absolutely
critical that we

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:15.380
strive in training to
put our salespeople

00:13:15.380 --> 00:13:18.340
into the seats, the professional
seats, of their buyers

00:13:18.340 --> 00:13:19.820
as best we could.

00:13:19.820 --> 00:13:23.980
So in our example, every
single HubSpot salesperson

00:13:23.980 --> 00:13:26.810
spends a good deal of
their 30 day training

00:13:26.810 --> 00:13:29.340
building their own
website and their own blog

00:13:29.340 --> 00:13:31.140
on the HubSpot software.

00:13:31.140 --> 00:13:32.990
They generate a
social media following

00:13:32.990 --> 00:13:36.380
of 100 plus followers for this
mini-business that they start.

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:39.070
They rank in Google
for dozens of words.

00:13:39.070 --> 00:13:42.000
They set up landing
pages and run A/B tests.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.500
They generate an email following
and nurture those emails.

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:50.261
They set up an
analytics platform

00:13:50.261 --> 00:13:52.260
so that they can actually
measure the conversion

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:54.410
rates between each one.

00:13:54.410 --> 00:13:56.700
And by the time they're
done with that training,

00:13:56.700 --> 00:13:59.460
they can actually school
90% of the marketers

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:01.800
that they're going to
speak with on the phone.

00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:04.110
And so I think that's a
big opportunity that I'd

00:14:04.110 --> 00:14:06.860
like to see more companies
do is go beyond just

00:14:06.860 --> 00:14:08.534
the typical product
training and try

00:14:08.534 --> 00:14:10.825
to get these folks engaged
in the day-to-day lives that

00:14:10.825 --> 00:14:12.040
are better sellers.

00:14:12.040 --> 00:14:15.720
The other opportunity
that we had was there's

00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:17.930
an opportunity for
the salespeople

00:14:17.930 --> 00:14:21.050
to build up their own
personal brand and trust

00:14:21.050 --> 00:14:23.820
within the ecosystem.

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:27.440
So many corporations and
brands are doing a better job

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:29.060
on their content
marketing strategy

00:14:29.060 --> 00:14:31.480
and their inbound marketing
strategy these days.

00:14:31.480 --> 00:14:34.380
And trying to come
up more organically,

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:37.210
whether it's in search or
social media discussions.

00:14:37.210 --> 00:14:40.860
That same opportunity
exists for the salespeople.

00:14:40.860 --> 00:14:44.900
And I encourage our salespeople.

00:14:44.900 --> 00:14:48.732
And even when I go out and
meet other salespeople,

00:14:48.732 --> 00:14:49.690
and they'll talk to me.

00:14:49.690 --> 00:14:53.320
They're like, Mark, I
cold call 50 hours a month

00:14:53.320 --> 00:14:56.880
in order to generate demand
for myself and my company.

00:14:56.880 --> 00:14:58.252
I say, that's the reality.

00:14:58.252 --> 00:14:58.960
It's a sales job.

00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:00.700
You need to cold call.

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:02.960
But here's what
I'd like you to do.

00:15:02.960 --> 00:15:06.170
Next month, spend 40 hours
a month cold calling.

00:15:06.170 --> 00:15:09.030
And use that 10 hours
a month that you saved

00:15:09.030 --> 00:15:13.320
and actually participate
online where your prospects

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:14.950
are actually conversing.

00:15:14.950 --> 00:15:18.920
So what blogs are your
prospects following?

00:15:18.920 --> 00:15:22.010
Read those blogs,
comment on those blogs.

00:15:22.010 --> 00:15:24.340
In fact, submit a guest
post for your blog

00:15:24.340 --> 00:15:25.710
if you have a corporate blog.

00:15:25.710 --> 00:15:28.235
What LinkedIn groups are
your prospects a part of?

00:15:28.235 --> 00:15:30.510
Get involved in
those LinkedIn groups

00:15:30.510 --> 00:15:33.400
and answer those questions.

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:35.620
On Twitter, who do
they follow on Twitter?

00:15:35.620 --> 00:15:37.769
Follow those same people,
and retweet their stuff.

00:15:37.769 --> 00:15:39.435
And you'd be surprised
that those people

00:15:39.435 --> 00:15:40.830
will start following you.

00:15:40.830 --> 00:15:42.163
And then do that for two months.

00:15:42.163 --> 00:15:45.190
And then ask yourself,
were those 10 hours a month

00:15:45.190 --> 00:15:48.230
spent better cold calling,
or were they spent better

00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:49.920
participating in social media?

00:15:49.920 --> 00:15:51.860
What kind of action did
that stir up for you?

00:15:51.860 --> 00:15:53.360
And I think most
salespeople find

00:15:53.360 --> 00:15:56.110
that that was a really
productive process,

00:15:56.110 --> 00:15:58.290
and they may actually double
down on those efforts.

00:15:58.290 --> 00:15:59.748
So there's certainly
an opportunity

00:15:59.748 --> 00:16:01.770
out there for
salespeople themselves

00:16:01.770 --> 00:16:03.576
to set themselves up
as thought leaders.

00:16:03.576 --> 00:16:05.450
And that's something
that can be incorporated

00:16:05.450 --> 00:16:08.420
into training as well.

00:16:08.420 --> 00:16:13.240
Third section, same quality
and quantity of leads.

00:16:13.240 --> 00:16:15.400
How many people in
the last six months

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:17.910
have received a cold call,
either at your office

00:16:17.910 --> 00:16:22.330
or at your home, and you got
into this engaging conversation

00:16:22.330 --> 00:16:24.900
with the telemarketer,
and you ended up buying

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:26.729
the product they were selling?

00:16:26.729 --> 00:16:29.020
There's usually like one,
like a timeshare or something

00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:30.610
like that.

00:16:30.610 --> 00:16:31.870
I had one that called me.

00:16:31.870 --> 00:16:34.610
He said, do you have a
crack in your windshield?

00:16:34.610 --> 00:16:35.110
I said no.

00:16:35.110 --> 00:16:37.240
And they just hung up.

00:16:37.240 --> 00:16:39.650
That's what these people
are doing in these jobs.

00:16:39.650 --> 00:16:42.440
I don't know why they do this.

00:16:42.440 --> 00:16:44.220
How many people in
the last six months

00:16:44.220 --> 00:16:47.720
have received a piece of direct
mail or an unsolicited email

00:16:47.720 --> 00:16:48.950
to your inbox?

00:16:48.950 --> 00:16:50.760
You opened it, you
were intrigued,

00:16:50.760 --> 00:16:53.070
and you ended up
buying the product.

00:16:53.070 --> 00:16:54.760
What was it?

00:16:54.760 --> 00:16:55.510
AUDIENCE: Clothes.

00:16:55.510 --> 00:16:56.426
MARK ROBERGE: Clothes?

00:16:56.426 --> 00:16:57.690
OK, you're fired from Google.

00:16:57.690 --> 00:16:59.550
You're not supposed to do this.

00:16:59.550 --> 00:17:00.140
That's cool.

00:17:00.140 --> 00:17:02.056
It's unique to find that
amongst the audience.

00:17:02.056 --> 00:17:02.950
But that's cool.

00:17:02.950 --> 00:17:03.930
What brand was it?

00:17:03.930 --> 00:17:05.119
They get me too.

00:17:05.119 --> 00:17:06.871
I always get the
catalogs and stuff.

00:17:06.871 --> 00:17:08.079
AUDIENCE: I'd rather not say.

00:17:08.079 --> 00:17:09.829
MARK ROBERGE: OK, that's cool.

00:17:09.829 --> 00:17:12.250
I'm a big fan of
Pistol Lake these days,

00:17:12.250 --> 00:17:14.069
like the startup
hoodie thing going on.

00:17:14.069 --> 00:17:16.470
But yeah, you don't
have to tell me.

00:17:16.470 --> 00:17:18.150
How many people in
the last six months

00:17:18.150 --> 00:17:22.849
have gone to Google to do a
search or out into social media

00:17:22.849 --> 00:17:24.230
to do some research
on a product,

00:17:24.230 --> 00:17:27.460
and that research led
to you buying a product?

00:17:27.460 --> 00:17:29.600
OK, so the folks in
this room has probably

00:17:29.600 --> 00:17:32.970
had the biggest influence of
any company on this trend.

00:17:32.970 --> 00:17:35.100
But this is the reality
of the buying journey

00:17:35.100 --> 00:17:37.800
that we're dealing
with today is buyers

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:39.630
have complete empowerment.

00:17:39.630 --> 00:17:41.970
And they don't have
to go to trade shows.

00:17:41.970 --> 00:17:44.630
They don't have to deal with
these interruptive outbound

00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:46.230
marketing, as we call it.

00:17:46.230 --> 00:17:48.900
They can be in their bunny
slippers on a Saturday night,

00:17:48.900 --> 00:17:50.670
doing research after
the kids are asleep,

00:17:50.670 --> 00:17:53.086
making business decisions and
choosing the vendors they're

00:17:53.086 --> 00:17:54.471
going to do business with.

00:17:54.471 --> 00:17:56.720
And what's really interesting
and still an opportunity

00:17:56.720 --> 00:17:59.675
for us, and obviously, a huge
amount that you guys continue

00:17:59.675 --> 00:18:04.730
to take advantage of, is
when you go back and resurvey

00:18:04.730 --> 00:18:06.864
most audiences and
ask them, where

00:18:06.864 --> 00:18:09.030
are they spending their
sales and marketing budgets?

00:18:09.030 --> 00:18:11.670
How much are they
spending on trade shows,

00:18:11.670 --> 00:18:14.740
and interruptive
advertising, and cold calling

00:18:14.740 --> 00:18:18.300
versus how much are they
putting into content

00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:22.180
and the efforts that can attract
people to their businesses?

00:18:22.180 --> 00:18:24.520
There's still a
huge disproportion

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:27.460
to the buyer behavior that we
just proved out in that survey

00:18:27.460 --> 00:18:29.094
and proves out time
and time again.

00:18:29.094 --> 00:18:30.760
And that's a big
opportunity, obviously,

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:34.240
that we've always tried to
push is this inbound marketing

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:36.800
message leading into content.

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:42.980
And the thing that most
businesses don't recognize

00:18:42.980 --> 00:18:46.460
is the importance of
content development

00:18:46.460 --> 00:18:48.390
and the journalist's
role in that.

00:18:48.390 --> 00:18:51.810
I was actually just speaking
to a startup on the way

00:18:51.810 --> 00:18:54.040
here, down in New York.

00:18:54.040 --> 00:18:57.180
100 people, starting to build
out their marketing team.

00:18:57.180 --> 00:19:00.320
And it amazes me, to this
day, that it knocks them

00:19:00.320 --> 00:19:03.460
off their seat when I tell
them that our second hire

00:19:03.460 --> 00:19:06.430
in our marketing team when
we were only 20 people

00:19:06.430 --> 00:19:08.660
was a journalist from
the "New York Times."

00:19:08.660 --> 00:19:11.070
And that's really how a lot
of these marketing teams

00:19:11.070 --> 00:19:12.470
need to be thinking.

00:19:12.470 --> 00:19:14.890
It's less about these folks
who have product marketing

00:19:14.890 --> 00:19:19.500
backgrounds, and trade show
booth skills, or direct mail

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:21.300
skills, and that kind of stuff.

00:19:21.300 --> 00:19:23.630
And it's more about
people can just

00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:30.470
speak to a neurologist with
a very deep PhD and great

00:19:30.470 --> 00:19:32.900
knowledge in a space that
they know nothing about,

00:19:32.900 --> 00:19:36.100
and actually take from that
hour-long cup of coffee

00:19:36.100 --> 00:19:39.630
a beautiful piece that
layman folks can understand.

00:19:39.630 --> 00:19:41.610
That's what a great
journalist can do.

00:19:41.610 --> 00:19:43.730
And that person
and that skill set

00:19:43.730 --> 00:19:46.920
plays an enormous role
in marketing teams today.

00:19:46.920 --> 00:19:49.230
It plays an enormous role
in the demand generation

00:19:49.230 --> 00:19:52.980
formula for many businesses.

00:19:52.980 --> 00:19:55.410
The great thing
about that is it's

00:19:55.410 --> 00:19:57.680
not a great time to be
a journalist these days

00:19:57.680 --> 00:19:59.580
in a traditional manner.

00:19:59.580 --> 00:20:03.340
The newspapers and magazines
are not exactly doing well.

00:20:03.340 --> 00:20:07.960
And these folks are far less
expensive than a programmer

00:20:07.960 --> 00:20:10.140
and far easier to find.

00:20:10.140 --> 00:20:13.155
So not even they know that they
hold the keys to the future

00:20:13.155 --> 00:20:14.230
of sales and marketing.

00:20:14.230 --> 00:20:17.810
So we hope to see more companies
take advantage of that.

00:20:17.810 --> 00:20:19.356
And the process
that we like to see

00:20:19.356 --> 00:20:20.730
is once you find
that journalist,

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:22.300
they don't have to
necessarily have

00:20:22.300 --> 00:20:24.930
domain experience
in the business

00:20:24.930 --> 00:20:26.370
that they're working in.

00:20:26.370 --> 00:20:27.990
That's really the
job of the business.

00:20:27.990 --> 00:20:30.360
The CEO, the C-suite,
the salespeople

00:20:30.360 --> 00:20:32.655
usually have great
knowledge of the domain

00:20:32.655 --> 00:20:34.960
because they're talking
to prospects all the time.

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:37.650
So when you find that
journalist, coupling them

00:20:37.650 --> 00:20:41.610
with a few dozen or dozens
of thought leadership folks,

00:20:41.610 --> 00:20:44.470
a committee, within the
organization is advantageous.

00:20:44.470 --> 00:20:47.510
And they can sit down once
a week for an hour with one

00:20:47.510 --> 00:20:50.070
thought leader, and
they can interview them

00:20:50.070 --> 00:20:54.770
and produce a five-page ebook,
and produce three or four blog

00:20:54.770 --> 00:20:59.720
posts, and produce a few dozen
social media messages that they

00:20:59.720 --> 00:21:01.820
can actually schedule
over the course of a month

00:21:01.820 --> 00:21:03.800
from that one interview.

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:06.360
And those social
media messages go out

00:21:06.360 --> 00:21:08.530
over the course of a month.

00:21:08.530 --> 00:21:11.000
They point back to the
relevant blog articles.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.610
And most importantly, at
the end of each blog article

00:21:13.610 --> 00:21:15.830
is a call to action
that says, did you

00:21:15.830 --> 00:21:17.230
like this blog article on XYZ?

00:21:17.230 --> 00:21:20.590
Perhaps you'd like the
five-page ebook that we wrote.

00:21:20.590 --> 00:21:22.790
And that is yours for free.

00:21:22.790 --> 00:21:25.190
We just need your name,
phone number, email address,

00:21:25.190 --> 00:21:27.340
and company, and
you can have it.

00:21:27.340 --> 00:21:30.340
And that simple process
that didn't put a big burden

00:21:30.340 --> 00:21:32.250
on the executive
leadership team, the sales

00:21:32.250 --> 00:21:34.590
team, the engineering team
for content development,

00:21:34.590 --> 00:21:38.750
really specialized it in someone
who can do that very well,

00:21:38.750 --> 00:21:40.279
creates a huge
following in Google.

00:21:40.279 --> 00:21:42.445
Lots of great organic traffic
coming to the website.

00:21:42.445 --> 00:21:45.380
A really high conversion
rate from visit

00:21:45.380 --> 00:21:46.920
to lead on your website.

00:21:46.920 --> 00:21:49.620
And a nice stream of quality
leads for the sales team.

00:21:49.620 --> 00:21:53.660
So this has done very
well for organizations.

00:21:53.660 --> 00:21:55.160
The other thing
that comes up a lot

00:21:55.160 --> 00:21:59.060
is aligning marketing
and sales, especially

00:21:59.060 --> 00:22:00.892
at that mid-market
company level.

00:22:00.892 --> 00:22:02.350
It's something that
we went through

00:22:02.350 --> 00:22:05.150
and a lot of our customers
go through as well.

00:22:05.150 --> 00:22:08.880
And a lot of the companies
that we go and visit,

00:22:08.880 --> 00:22:11.510
we find that marketing and
sales has traditionally

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:12.850
not gotten along.

00:22:12.850 --> 00:22:14.500
I don't know if
you guys have gone

00:22:14.500 --> 00:22:15.910
through that at some point.

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:17.490
You probably did.

00:22:17.490 --> 00:22:19.690
What I find often
is that marketers

00:22:19.690 --> 00:22:23.370
feel that their salespeople
are overpaid spoiled brats.

00:22:23.370 --> 00:22:25.150
And the salespeople
feel that marketers

00:22:25.150 --> 00:22:26.920
do arts and crafts all day.

00:22:26.920 --> 00:22:28.890
And that's the reality
of that relationship.

00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:31.540
And then they go back to
their respective corners

00:22:31.540 --> 00:22:34.050
of the office, and
do their cold calls

00:22:34.050 --> 00:22:37.110
and do their trade show
booths and branding exercises.

00:22:37.110 --> 00:22:38.700
And there's dysfunction.

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:41.740
And that dysfunction
is the kiss of death

00:22:41.740 --> 00:22:45.130
in today's modern organization
when so many buying journeys

00:22:45.130 --> 00:22:48.470
start online and need
to be eloquently passed

00:22:48.470 --> 00:22:50.560
off to the salesperson.

00:22:50.560 --> 00:22:53.000
So this alignment is
really, really critical,

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.770
and something that we worked
hard on in quantifying.

00:22:55.770 --> 00:22:57.670
And so that's the first step.

00:22:57.670 --> 00:23:01.380
We created this sales and
marketing SLA, service level

00:23:01.380 --> 00:23:04.810
agreement, where we quantified
the deliverables from marketing

00:23:04.810 --> 00:23:07.040
to sales and sales to marketing.

00:23:07.040 --> 00:23:09.930
So as an example, we
knew in the first year

00:23:09.930 --> 00:23:13.570
or two of our business that
for a mid-market salesperson,

00:23:13.570 --> 00:23:16.220
if we gave them 100
inbound leads a month,

00:23:16.220 --> 00:23:18.370
that they would
connect with half,

00:23:18.370 --> 00:23:21.130
create 30 sales
opportunities, do 15 demos,

00:23:21.130 --> 00:23:24.310
and close 5 customers
for roughly $800 monthly

00:23:24.310 --> 00:23:26.230
recurring revenue per customer.

00:23:26.230 --> 00:23:29.200
And that math worked very well.

00:23:29.200 --> 00:23:32.880
So if we had 10 mid-market
salespeople, each needing 100

00:23:32.880 --> 00:23:35.060
leads a month, it was
very easy to define

00:23:35.060 --> 00:23:40.330
that SLA of 1,000
mid-market qualified sales

00:23:40.330 --> 00:23:41.280
leads for that team.

00:23:41.280 --> 00:23:43.600
And that was the journey
that marketing had to follow.

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:45.040
Sounds really good.

00:23:45.040 --> 00:23:48.110
And if I found a company that
did that, I would say, great.

00:23:48.110 --> 00:23:49.960
You're in the top
5% of your peers

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:53.070
in terms of the sales and
marketing alignment journey.

00:23:53.070 --> 00:23:55.450
However, even that
sophistication

00:23:55.450 --> 00:23:57.090
created misalignment.

00:23:57.090 --> 00:24:02.730
And what happened was we
counted a VP of marketing

00:24:02.730 --> 00:24:04.930
who came to our
website and requested

00:24:04.930 --> 00:24:07.170
a demo as a qualified lead.

00:24:07.170 --> 00:24:08.870
That was beautiful.

00:24:08.870 --> 00:24:11.550
We also counted
a VP of marketing

00:24:11.550 --> 00:24:14.070
from a mid-market company
that download a white paper

00:24:14.070 --> 00:24:15.650
as a qualified lead.

00:24:15.650 --> 00:24:17.120
That's a great lead.

00:24:17.120 --> 00:24:21.160
Now any guesses as to which
one closed at a higher rate?

00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:26.140
The demo request or the
white paper download?

00:24:26.140 --> 00:24:26.820
Demo request.

00:24:26.820 --> 00:24:28.660
It was about three times higher.

00:24:28.660 --> 00:24:31.990
And which one is easier
for marketing to generate?

00:24:31.990 --> 00:24:34.010
To get a visitor
to request a demo

00:24:34.010 --> 00:24:36.000
or to get them to
download a white paper?

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:36.500
Right?

00:24:36.500 --> 00:24:40.560
So even though we were pretty
sophisticated in our approach,

00:24:40.560 --> 00:24:42.350
it still created a misalignment.

00:24:42.350 --> 00:24:45.760
And sure enough, as the
month or quarter unfolded

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:48.830
and the marketing team
fell behind in their SLA,

00:24:48.830 --> 00:24:50.860
all the calls to
actions on the website

00:24:50.860 --> 00:24:53.040
moved from demo requests
to white paper downloads.

00:24:53.040 --> 00:24:53.950
And the sales team
was like, what

00:24:53.950 --> 00:24:56.060
happened to those
beautiful demo requests?

00:24:56.060 --> 00:24:59.660
So Mike Volpe, our CMO and I,
sat back and thought about it.

00:24:59.660 --> 00:25:02.830
And we're studying
the lead flow.

00:25:02.830 --> 00:25:07.280
And let's take the mid-market
example in the upper-right.

00:25:07.280 --> 00:25:10.270
We studied tens of thousands of
leads that were at the problem

00:25:10.270 --> 00:25:11.720
education stage.

00:25:11.720 --> 00:25:13.740
They had downloaded
white papers.

00:25:13.740 --> 00:25:16.140
And those converted
to customers at 2%.

00:25:16.140 --> 00:25:19.451
And when they bought software
from us, they spent $200,000.

00:25:19.451 --> 00:25:20.450
I made these numbers up.

00:25:20.450 --> 00:25:22.410
But you get the point.

00:25:22.410 --> 00:25:24.330
Versus if someone
went all the way down

00:25:24.330 --> 00:25:27.362
to the solution research
stage and requested a demo,

00:25:27.362 --> 00:25:29.320
well, they would close
at three times the rate.

00:25:29.320 --> 00:25:33.510
They'd close at 6% and
again, would spend $200,000

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:34.959
when they bought software.

00:25:34.959 --> 00:25:36.750
So we simply multiplied
the conversion rate

00:25:36.750 --> 00:25:38.375
times the average
revenue per customer,

00:25:38.375 --> 00:25:41.010
and that got us a lead value.

00:25:41.010 --> 00:25:46.600
So now, white paper
downloads were worth $4,000,

00:25:46.600 --> 00:25:49.850
and demo request were worth 12.

00:25:49.850 --> 00:25:53.170
And now I was in a
position to tell marketing,

00:25:53.170 --> 00:25:56.060
I no longer need 1,000
mid-market leads from you

00:25:56.060 --> 00:25:56.900
a month.

00:25:56.900 --> 00:26:01.440
I need $700,000 of lead value.

00:26:01.440 --> 00:26:03.410
And whether you
get there through,

00:26:03.410 --> 00:26:08.720
whatever the math is, 1,000 or
so of the white paper downloads

00:26:08.720 --> 00:26:12.860
or 3,000 or so of the demo
requests, that's up to you.

00:26:12.860 --> 00:26:15.640
And this was a very,
very effective concept

00:26:15.640 --> 00:26:18.510
and a cool concept when
you think we put marketing

00:26:18.510 --> 00:26:21.160
on a revenue quota
just like sales,

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:23.360
and that kind of
accountability month to month.

00:26:23.360 --> 00:26:25.840
And suddenly, literally,
the next week,

00:26:25.840 --> 00:26:28.700
all the calls to actions on the
website went to demo requests.

00:26:28.700 --> 00:26:29.650
And it was great.

00:26:29.650 --> 00:26:31.360
Sales loved them,
more qualified leads.

00:26:31.360 --> 00:26:33.425
And marketing was getting
the appropriate credit

00:26:33.425 --> 00:26:34.800
for the hard work
they were doing

00:26:34.800 --> 00:26:36.450
in driving that quality lead.

00:26:36.450 --> 00:26:40.980
Now sales does not get off
the hook with this process.

00:26:40.980 --> 00:26:42.570
They're equally accountable.

00:26:42.570 --> 00:26:45.700
And what I would do is I'd
ask questions like, OK, when

00:26:45.700 --> 00:26:49.554
I get a qualified lead, I know
we should call it right away.

00:26:49.554 --> 00:26:50.470
I know we should call.

00:26:50.470 --> 00:26:55.980
But if I do get voicemail, do
I call it this afternoon again,

00:26:55.980 --> 00:26:58.240
or tomorrow, or next week?

00:26:58.240 --> 00:26:59.690
Or when should I try it again?

00:26:59.690 --> 00:27:01.960
And how many times should
I try it before I give up?

00:27:01.960 --> 00:27:04.890
And as a sales leader, should I
give each salesperson one lead

00:27:04.890 --> 00:27:07.397
a month and have them
call it 1,000 times?

00:27:07.397 --> 00:27:09.105
Or give them 1,000
leads a month and have

00:27:09.105 --> 00:27:10.589
them call them once each?

00:27:10.589 --> 00:27:12.880
So obviously, the right answer
is somewhere in between.

00:27:12.880 --> 00:27:14.580
But where is that right answer?

00:27:14.580 --> 00:27:16.805
So another study, to
give you some examples

00:27:16.805 --> 00:27:19.510
of some of this stuff,
stuff that you guys

00:27:19.510 --> 00:27:23.450
do quite well as well,
is here, the x-axis

00:27:23.450 --> 00:27:26.690
is the number of attempts
we made against these leads.

00:27:26.690 --> 00:27:27.990
Some were only attempted twice.

00:27:27.990 --> 00:27:30.820
Some were attempted 12 times.

00:27:30.820 --> 00:27:34.660
And the y-axis is the
profitability of those efforts.

00:27:34.660 --> 00:27:37.694
Because clearly, when you call
something more frequently,

00:27:37.694 --> 00:27:39.610
your likelihood to get
on the phone is higher,

00:27:39.610 --> 00:27:42.020
but it costs you more
in terms of your pursuit

00:27:42.020 --> 00:27:43.320
of that account.

00:27:43.320 --> 00:27:46.602
So wherever we could
maximize these behaviors

00:27:46.602 --> 00:27:48.810
in terms of profitability,
that was the right answer.

00:27:48.810 --> 00:27:52.310
So the orange line was
the small business leads,

00:27:52.310 --> 00:27:54.546
and that maxed out
at around 5 attempts.

00:27:54.546 --> 00:27:55.920
The blue line was
the mid-market.

00:27:55.920 --> 00:27:57.810
That maxed out
around 8 attempts.

00:27:57.810 --> 00:28:01.362
And the black line
was 12 attempts.

00:28:01.362 --> 00:28:02.820
The black was the
enterprise leads,

00:28:02.820 --> 00:28:04.340
and that maxed out
at 12 attempts.

00:28:04.340 --> 00:28:07.210
So now I could go to the
sales team and say, guys,

00:28:07.210 --> 00:28:10.900
we have calculated the behavior
to making the most money here

00:28:10.900 --> 00:28:12.180
at HubSpot.

00:28:12.180 --> 00:28:14.680
And that's what
salespeople like to hear.

00:28:14.680 --> 00:28:16.720
And guys, we programmed
this into the CRM.

00:28:16.720 --> 00:28:18.530
You don't even have
to think about it.

00:28:18.530 --> 00:28:20.820
You go, you call lead.

00:28:20.820 --> 00:28:22.900
The CRM automatically
notes that call

00:28:22.900 --> 00:28:25.420
and puts that lead away, and
brings it back the next time

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:26.700
it should call.

00:28:26.700 --> 00:28:28.190
And each night,
we're going to have

00:28:28.190 --> 00:28:30.770
a report that goes out to
make sure that nothing's

00:28:30.770 --> 00:28:32.670
fallen through the cracks.

00:28:32.670 --> 00:28:34.500
And salespeople like
that, too, if you

00:28:34.500 --> 00:28:37.370
start with a very
data-driven culture.

00:28:37.370 --> 00:28:39.340
They like the fact that
this is my lead flow.

00:28:39.340 --> 00:28:41.497
And I want to make sure
I'm optimizing the revenue

00:28:41.497 --> 00:28:42.330
from that lead flow.

00:28:42.330 --> 00:28:44.800
And I'm glad that the
system checks it for me.

00:28:44.800 --> 00:28:47.350
So each night, a report
went out to the whole sales

00:28:47.350 --> 00:28:50.370
team, the whole marketing
team, me, our CEO.

00:28:50.370 --> 00:28:52.582
And it showed if any
of these behaviors

00:28:52.582 --> 00:28:54.290
were not being followed
by the sales team

00:28:54.290 --> 00:28:56.050
so we could act immediately.

00:28:56.050 --> 00:28:59.180
And it also showed where we
were on this marketing SLA

00:28:59.180 --> 00:29:01.170
so the marketing
team was accountable.

00:29:01.170 --> 00:29:04.000
So we were able to
manage that demand gen

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:06.470
handoff on a daily
basis to make sure

00:29:06.470 --> 00:29:08.639
that we had the right
demand feeding to the team

00:29:08.639 --> 00:29:10.180
and to make sure
that that demand was

00:29:10.180 --> 00:29:12.780
being acted on appropriately
by the sales folks.

00:29:12.780 --> 00:29:15.450
And we were intervening
immediately if it wasn't.

00:29:15.450 --> 00:29:18.380
So that helped us
out quite a bit.

00:29:18.380 --> 00:29:23.400
Last section, then I'll
move to the questions.

00:29:23.400 --> 00:29:27.910
So managing
salespeople and holding

00:29:27.910 --> 00:29:31.000
them accountable to
the same sales process.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:33.900
I wish we could rename
the sales management

00:29:33.900 --> 00:29:37.132
title to the sales coaches.

00:29:37.132 --> 00:29:39.090
Because I think that's
the most important thing

00:29:39.090 --> 00:29:41.150
that sales managers
can do is coach

00:29:41.150 --> 00:29:43.260
and develop their salespeople.

00:29:43.260 --> 00:29:46.020
And the best and
simplest example

00:29:46.020 --> 00:29:49.170
I can give in what I see
as effective coaching

00:29:49.170 --> 00:29:51.300
comes from my
pursuit of the game

00:29:51.300 --> 00:29:55.160
of golf, which has not been a
very successful pursuit today.

00:29:55.160 --> 00:29:57.090
But I've taken many lessons.

00:29:57.090 --> 00:29:59.880
And one golf pro said,
Mark, take a swing.

00:29:59.880 --> 00:30:01.290
And I did.

00:30:01.290 --> 00:30:04.000
And he said, OK, turn your
grip over a little bit.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:05.250
Lean back in your stance.

00:30:05.250 --> 00:30:07.549
Put more weight on your
right foot not your left.

00:30:07.549 --> 00:30:09.590
Think 1 o'clock not 2
o'clock on your back swing.

00:30:09.590 --> 00:30:12.120
And turn your wrist over more
when you contact the ball.

00:30:12.120 --> 00:30:15.020
And I was like, you
gotta be kidding me.

00:30:15.020 --> 00:30:17.480
The next golf pro was like,
all right, Mark, take a swing.

00:30:17.480 --> 00:30:18.240
And I did.

00:30:18.240 --> 00:30:21.590
And he said, all right, turn
your grip over a little bit.

00:30:21.590 --> 00:30:23.410
Now take a hundred swings.

00:30:23.410 --> 00:30:24.592
I did that for 20 minutes.

00:30:24.592 --> 00:30:25.800
And he said, how's that feel?

00:30:25.800 --> 00:30:26.966
I said, yeah, I can feel it.

00:30:26.966 --> 00:30:27.930
That feels good.

00:30:27.930 --> 00:30:30.340
So now start leaning back
in your stance a little bit.

00:30:30.340 --> 00:30:31.735
Take another hundred swings.

00:30:31.735 --> 00:30:33.190
How's that feel?

00:30:33.190 --> 00:30:34.640
So a really simple example.

00:30:34.640 --> 00:30:38.620
But I have promoted 17
sales managers at HubSpot.

00:30:38.620 --> 00:30:42.030
Every single one falls into
the trap of the first golf pro.

00:30:42.030 --> 00:30:44.140
Where they get a
new salesperson,

00:30:44.140 --> 00:30:46.150
and they see the
90 things that are

00:30:46.150 --> 00:30:48.110
broken with them of
where they are today

00:30:48.110 --> 00:30:50.470
and where they want them
to be, and they throw up

00:30:50.470 --> 00:30:52.750
on them for an
hour with feedback.

00:30:52.750 --> 00:30:54.750
And you can just see
the rep's head spinning,

00:30:54.750 --> 00:30:56.660
and they don't know
where to start.

00:30:56.660 --> 00:30:59.410
And the best sales
managers and coaches

00:30:59.410 --> 00:31:04.070
can actually see the 90 things
but focus on the one or two

00:31:04.070 --> 00:31:07.010
that are going to make
the biggest impact today.

00:31:07.010 --> 00:31:10.910
And they decipher and
diagnose that through metrics.

00:31:10.910 --> 00:31:13.310
And I call that
metric-driven sales coaching.

00:31:13.310 --> 00:31:16.140
And let me show you an
example of how that works.

00:31:16.140 --> 00:31:19.840
So here's a really
simple sales funnel.

00:31:19.840 --> 00:31:22.380
In the very
upper-left, you've got

00:31:22.380 --> 00:31:25.210
how many leads each rep worked.

00:31:25.210 --> 00:31:26.867
How many they generated.

00:31:26.867 --> 00:31:27.950
Then how many they worked.

00:31:27.950 --> 00:31:29.199
How many demos they delivered.

00:31:29.199 --> 00:31:30.734
And how much
revenue they closed.

00:31:30.734 --> 00:31:32.650
The different colors are
different salespeople

00:31:32.650 --> 00:31:33.664
in a given month.

00:31:33.664 --> 00:31:35.080
And on the right-hand
side, you've

00:31:35.080 --> 00:31:38.120
got the conversion
rates between each.

00:31:38.120 --> 00:31:43.270
So just to throw out
some examples here.

00:31:43.270 --> 00:31:47.230
Let's look at the
top person in purple.

00:31:47.230 --> 00:31:50.200
So if you were
their sales manager,

00:31:50.200 --> 00:31:52.420
be a brave soul
here and tell me,

00:31:52.420 --> 00:31:55.024
what would your coaching
diagnosis be here?

00:31:55.024 --> 00:31:56.440
What do you see
in their activity,

00:31:56.440 --> 00:32:00.503
and where are they broken
in the sales process?

00:32:00.503 --> 00:32:02.390
AUDIENCE: They're not
bringing in revenue.

00:32:02.390 --> 00:32:03.370
MARK ROBERGE: Yeah, low revenue.

00:32:03.370 --> 00:32:04.102
AUDIENCE: Demos.

00:32:04.102 --> 00:32:06.213
Lower demos than when you
look at who's coming in

00:32:06.213 --> 00:32:07.195
with the most revenue.

00:32:07.195 --> 00:32:10.141
So potentially, if they focused
more of their time doing demos,

00:32:10.141 --> 00:32:13.524
little less of their
time doing leads work,

00:32:13.524 --> 00:32:15.565
and really finding the
ones that are working well

00:32:15.565 --> 00:32:18.526
for them, transitioning
those to demos quicker.

00:32:18.526 --> 00:32:19.900
Then they might
get more revenue.

00:32:19.900 --> 00:32:20.733
MARK ROBERGE: Right.

00:32:20.733 --> 00:32:23.850
So she said, maybe a little
less focus working leads,

00:32:23.850 --> 00:32:24.610
little more demos.

00:32:24.610 --> 00:32:25.840
And that could get
to higher revenue.

00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:27.270
I think that's a good diagnosis.

00:32:27.270 --> 00:32:30.750
And what's interesting, whenever
I go to a non metrics-driven

00:32:30.750 --> 00:32:33.840
manager, whenever they have
an underperforming rep,

00:32:33.840 --> 00:32:36.240
they usually say, it's
an activity problem.

00:32:36.240 --> 00:32:37.855
They just need to
do more activity.

00:32:37.855 --> 00:32:40.410
And in this case, that's
far from the truth.

00:32:40.410 --> 00:32:44.050
This person in purple at the
top is doing the most activity.

00:32:44.050 --> 00:32:45.460
They're sourcing the most leads.

00:32:45.460 --> 00:32:48.100
They're doing the second
most calls on the team.

00:32:48.100 --> 00:32:50.750
But they're really bad at
getting them to the demo stage.

00:32:50.750 --> 00:32:52.979
And they're really bad at
converting them to revenue.

00:32:52.979 --> 00:32:55.020
And so we've got two
problems we have to work on.

00:32:55.020 --> 00:32:57.600
We have to work on getting
prospecting demands to the demo

00:32:57.600 --> 00:32:58.100
stage.

00:32:58.100 --> 00:33:00.440
And we have to work on
closing demos to customers.

00:33:00.440 --> 00:33:02.950
And I personally like to
start as high in the funnel

00:33:02.950 --> 00:33:04.654
as I see a problem.

00:33:04.654 --> 00:33:06.070
I can work on the
demo, but I just

00:33:06.070 --> 00:33:09.180
don't feel like we have enough
at bat, as you pointed out.

00:33:09.180 --> 00:33:12.301
So I need to look at the
leads that are working

00:33:12.301 --> 00:33:14.300
and their effectiveness
at getting to the demos.

00:33:14.300 --> 00:33:17.660
And my first question always is,
can I learn more from the data

00:33:17.660 --> 00:33:18.610
by double-clicking?

00:33:18.610 --> 00:33:21.400
And in this case, I can
in this simple example.

00:33:21.400 --> 00:33:25.400
So it's either that they
are working lots of leads

00:33:25.400 --> 00:33:28.050
but not getting them on
the phone, in which case, I

00:33:28.050 --> 00:33:31.310
will see a lower connect rate
in the upper right-hand corner.

00:33:31.310 --> 00:33:33.600
Or it's that they're
getting them on the phone,

00:33:33.600 --> 00:33:35.895
but they are terrible
at breaking the ice

00:33:35.895 --> 00:33:37.770
and getting them to move
forward in the sales

00:33:37.770 --> 00:33:39.445
process, in which
case, I would show

00:33:39.445 --> 00:33:41.640
a deficiency in the
bottom right chart.

00:33:41.640 --> 00:33:44.190
And this is an
important analysis

00:33:44.190 --> 00:33:46.440
because my coaching's going
to be very, very different

00:33:46.440 --> 00:33:47.990
depending on my finding.

00:33:47.990 --> 00:33:49.720
If I find that their
connect rate's low,

00:33:49.720 --> 00:33:52.530
